fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Let \mathbb {I} be an interval object with distinct endpoints 0,1; write 
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrack -\right \rbrack \mathclose {}
\colon \mathbb {I}\hookrightarrow  \mathsf {Prop} for the embedding sending x:\mathbb {I} to 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x=1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We then inherit a partial order \leq  on \mathbb {I} from the implication order along 
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrack -\right \rbrack \mathclose {}
. We will write \mathbb {I}_2 for the subset type 
 \mathopen {}\left \lbrace 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
:\mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I}\,\middle \vert \,x \leq  y\right \rbrace \mathclose {}
.

html:ol.html:li:
The evaluation map 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to  \mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I} factors through the inclusion \iota _2\colon  \mathbb {I}_2 \hookrightarrow  \mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I} along an isomorphism H\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to  \mathbb {I}_2.

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
First we check that for each \phi \colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}, we have \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\leq  \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. We calculate using our assumption:

Therefore, 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to  \mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I} factors through \iota _2\colon  \mathbb {I}_2 \hookrightarrow  \mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I} along some map H\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to  \mathbb {I}_2. We will show that H is an isomorphism by explicitly defining an inverse H^{-1} \colon  \mathbb {I}_2\to  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}:

fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
 H^{-1}
\mathopen {}\left \lparen x\leq  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
:\equiv  \lambda {z}\mathpunct {.} x \lor  
\mathopen {}\left \lparen z\land  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}

  \begin {aligned}
   \iota _2
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen H
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen H^{-1}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\leq  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   &=

 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen H^{-1}
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\leq  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   \\
   &= 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \lambda {z}\mathpunct {.} x \lor  
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen z\land  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   \\
   &= 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\lor 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0 \land  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, x\lor 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 1\land  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   \\
   &= 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x, x\lor  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   \\
   &= 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x,y\right \rparen \mathclose {}

   \\
   &= \iota _2
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\leq  y\right \rparen \mathclose {}

  \end {aligned}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Assuming the described factorisation property, we fix \phi \colon  \mathbb {I}\to \mathbb {I} to check that \phi  = \lambda {x}\mathpunct {.}\phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\lor 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\land  \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
. Because H\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to  \mathbb {I}_2 is an isomorphism (and therefore an embedding), it follows that 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*\colon  \mathbb {I}^\mathbb {I}\to \mathbb {I}\times \mathbb {I} is an embedding. Therefore it suffices to show that 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*\phi = 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0,1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
^*
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen \lambda {x}\mathpunct {.}\phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\lor 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen x\land \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\right \rparen \mathclose {}
.

Above we have used the fact that \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 0\right \rparen \mathclose {}
\leq \phi 
 \mathopen {}\left \lparen 1\right \rparen \mathclose {}
, which follows from the factorisation property.
